    	<h2><a name="2003-12-23" href="#2003-12-23"><font color="#660000">2003-12-23</font></a></h2>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107219769807558830">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h2>Più Miscellanea</h2>Here are even more random gleanings.&nbsp; I was lying awake thinking about things this morning, as part of gathering my thoughts for some writing.&nbsp; So, one thing is to find a way to operate more actively with this blog and also start organizing material.&nbsp; With regard to organization, it is possible to edit anything.&nbsp; My approach is not to edit anything but recent material.  And for older archived material, I want to do any editing on my web site rather than via Blogger.&nbsp; Because Blogger pages are "purpled," I also don't want to mangle the archive much because I don't know what link someone may have bookmarked (being the perpetual optimist about some things).&nbsp; What I prefer to do is annotate blogs rather than mangle them or hack them up.&nbsp; At some time, I must make something out of all these research notes that I have accumulated.&nbsp; The start of a new year is an interesting boundary point.&nbsp; I should freeze the material that is, say, more than 3-4 months old, and remove them from the Blogger archiving attention.&nbsp; I will make a job jar about that.&nbsp; Watch this space.<br /><br /><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/issues/2003/03/rauch.htm">The Atlantic | March 2003 | Caring for Your Introvert | Rauch</a>.&nbsp; Something to look at more closely when I have a moment.&nbsp; A find from Chris Dent.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107219769807558830">Tuesday, December 23, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	
    	<h2><a name="2003-12-22" href="#2003-12-22"><font color="#660000">2003-12-22</font></a></h2>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107213114140857000">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www-csli.stanford.edu/Archive/monthly/month8">CSLI Monthly 2, 5 (February 1987)</a>.&nbsp; This issue has an exchange between Terry Winograd and John Perry about reality, realism, and questions of how language is being used in Winograd & Flores.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107213114140857000">Monday, December 22, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107212965663789901">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=637096&jmp=references&dl=GUIDE&dl=ACM">A language/action perspective on the design of cooperative work</a>.&nbsp; I am out searching for something else of Terry Winograd's, but this is something I need to come back to.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107212965663789901">Monday, December 22, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107212634484789369">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.dif.unige.it/epi/art.htm">In defens of forest!</a>.&nbsp; This is a list of papers that may be consulted at the University of Genoa, Epistemology Section.&nbsp; I found this fascinating list while looking for a paper by Terry Winograd.&nbsp; I like having this link.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107212634484789369">Monday, December 22, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	
    	<h2><a name="2003-12-21" href="#2003-12-21"><font color="#660000">2003-12-21</font></a></h2>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107207514149017787">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://xnap.sourceforge.net/">XNap - News</a>.&nbsp; XNap is a plug-in based P2P framework written in Java.&nbsp; I don't know about the Java part, but the protocol plug-ins could be interesting.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107207514149017787">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107207480006422282">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://bitconjurer.org/BitTorrent/index.html">BitTorrent: News</a>.&nbsp; BitTorrent is apparently a file streaming service that uses tit-for-tat protocols so that distribution is aided by requiring downloaders to also serve as sources.&nbsp; It is not clear how well all of this might work for Miser distributed objects, but I want to keep my eye on it.&nbsp; There is a very active Java implementation on SourceForge.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107207480006422282">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107203779020946032">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://web.media.mit.edu/~minsky/">Marvin Minsky Home Page</a>.&nbsp; Marvin Minsky is writing a book called <em>The Emotion Machine</em> and drafts are available on his site.&nbsp; One of the features of human cognitive behavior is the ability to adapt, to abandon one plan, find another, and otherwise be resilient or ductile, depending on ones perspective.&nbsp; I am interested in how one could propose to codify such a thing, and also deal with it formally.&nbsp; It almost seems to be completely contradictory and antagonistic to a formal approach.&nbsp; Even so, I want to see what the connection is, if any.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107203779020946032">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107203640837409125">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://pintday.org/hack/crypto/ca.shtml">pintday.org: Certificate Authorities Demystified</a>.&nbsp; An interesting article with good discussion about self-signing and also creating a CA for X.509.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107203640837409125">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107203613496698382">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://tls.macrobyte.net/">MR: TLS | Home</a>.&nbsp; This site offers a commercial product.&nbsp; My interest in it has to do with the incorporation of the following procedures: <br /><br />"Macrobyte's TLS provides client side tools for making secure HTTPS requests, and server side tools for running a secure web server. It also includes tools for creating and managing 'keys,' self-signed certificates, and 'certificate signing requests' (for sending to companies like Verisign, Thawte, or Komodo, to receive a valid server certificate). "<br /><br />Now what I'd like to find is open specification of those protocols and any open-source implementation of tools for engaging them.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107203613496698382">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107203599679078195">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.quiltaholic.com/rickk/sslwrap/">SSLWrap</a>.&nbsp; This software provides a way to encrypt traffic over TCP.&nbsp; However, it creates a private-key exposure with a self-signed certification, so I wonder what that is about.&nbsp; Something to look at concerning the trust points involved.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107203599679078195">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107203585487550886">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://jedi.informatik.uni-leipzig.de/Docs/icswg003.html">Planning, Installing, and Using</a>.&nbsp; I just ran into a thread on self-signed certificates and how to use them with SSL, etc.&nbsp; Something I want to understand better, so I did the recommended search on "self-signed certificates" and this is one of the first hits.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107203585487550886">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107203428028229822">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://labyrinth.iaf.ac.at/2001/Nilges.html">Edward G. Nilges: On the Culture of Data Base/ Labyrinth vol. 3, Winter 2001</a>.&nbsp; The comp.software-eng newsgroup has a thread on Derrida and although there are some amazingly opinionated dismissals, Nilges offered up a different kind of appraisal.&nbsp; Here is an essay that he offers as relevant to the topic.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107203428028229822">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107203354569483755">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.tigris.org/">Tigris.org: Open Source Software Engineering</a>.&nbsp; A site devoted specifically to Open Source SE and appropriate tools.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107203354569483755">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107203298837959290">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.isospice.com/standard/is15504.htm">ISO/IEC 15504</a>.&nbsp; Here's an indication of where the TR 15504 is going to become an IS/IEC Standard Recommendation.&nbsp; There is some interesting background on usage of TR 1554 and the work on SPICE.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107203298837959290">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="10720289810800347">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.go-mono.com/">Home / Mono</a>.&nbsp; The Mono Project provides a C# compiler and a working interpreter.&nbsp; The compiler also works on .NET.&nbsp; One of the things that I find is that there are difficulties tracking with .NET development.&nbsp; On top of that, Mono is not supporting CAS, Code Access Security.&nbsp; This may be a problem for what I care about.&nbsp; I wonder whether this is part of ECMA or not, and how that will be sorted out.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#10720289810800347">Sunday, December 21, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>


